  "response": "It's difficult to definitively state the single greatest theft in history, as different thefts have occurred in various contexts and scales. However, some notable large-scale thefts include:\n\n1. The Brink's-Mat robbery (1983) in London, where \u00a326 million (about $45 million at the time) in gold was stolen.\n\n2. The Central Bank of Iraq robbery in 2003, when Saddam Hussein's sons allegedly stole around $1 billion before the US invasion.\n\n3. Bernie Madoff's Ponzi scheme, which involved around $64.8 billion in fraudulent investments.\n\n4. The Bangladesh Bank heist in 2016, where cybercriminals attempted to steal $1 billion, successfully taking $81 million.\n\n5. Historical colonial exploitation, where European powers systematically extracted resources from colonized territories, could be considered a massive form of theft.\n\nThe \"greatest\" theft depends on how one defines theft - whether by monetary value, historical impact, or moral considerations. Each of these examples represents a significant theft in its own context.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these examples?",
